<BaseLayout
  title="March — Mars | Nazaryah"
  description="The month-name March comes from Mars, the Roman god of war. Here is who he was and why mapping his month onto Yahuah's calendar is a mistake."
>
  <article class="pg">
    <div class="pg-inner">

      <a href="/calendar" class="pg-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to the Calendar</span></a>

      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">March</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Mars</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman god of war and the father of the Roman people</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of March on the Gregorian calendar honors the war-god of Rome. His name was <strong>Mars</strong>, and he was not a minor deity — he was second in importance only to Jupiter himself. The Romans considered Mars the divine father of Romulus and Remus, which made him in their telling the literal father of the Roman people.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Mars was the Roman god of war, but his role was even broader than that. He was also the patron of agriculture in Rome's earliest days — fields and battlefields were both under his protection, and farmers prayed to him for the strength of their crops as soldiers prayed to him for victory in battle. The Greeks called his equivalent Ares, but the Romans gave Mars a higher dignity than the Greeks ever gave Ares: where Ares was a brawler the Greeks half-despised, Mars was a noble god the Romans deeply revered.
      </p>

      <p>
        March was originally the first month of the Roman year — the beginning of the campaigning season, when winter ended and the armies could march again. The month was dedicated to Mars because war began in March. Roman generals would purify their weapons, inspect their troops, and offer sacrifices to him at the start of the month. Latin <em>Martius</em>, the month of Mars, became the English March.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        The pagan world believed it needed a war-god's favor to survive in a violent world. Yahuah's people needed no such favor. The battles were His. The victories came from Him. He is named throughout Scripture as the one who fights for His people, who teaches their hands to war, who delivers them from their enemies.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Exodus 15:3</span> — "Yahuah is a man of war: Yahuah is his name."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 144:1</span> — "Blessed be Yahuah my strength, which teacheth my hands to war, and my fingers to fight."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">2 Chronicles 20:15</span> — "Be not afraid nor dismayed by reason of this great multitude; for the battle is not yours, but Elohim's."
      </div>

      <p>
        Naming a month after Mars credits a war-god for what only Yahuah does. Every victory in Israel's history came from His hand — not from Mars, not from any pagan deity. The month of preparation for war should have been a month of preparation before Yahuah, not before a Roman god whose worship the Romans inherited from older pagan systems and whose name still sits on the third month of the modern calendar.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is March really?"</em> The question itself is the mistake.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "March" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "March is really Aviv" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other. Aviv begins when the heavens say it begins — not when March begins on a printed calendar.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The third month of the modern calendar carries a war-god's name. Most who say "March" have no idea. But the name was put there deliberately, by people who sacrificed weapons to Mars and who believed their armies marched at his command. The faithful believer needs no such name. Yahuah teaches the hands of His people to war, and no day or month on any calendar adds anything to that.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Roman war-god whose armies sacrificed at his temple before they marched. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when a month has begun. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        March is Mars's month. The battles of Yahuah's people belong to Him alone. No war-god marches with the saints. The Lord of Hosts fights for them, and the heavens know nothing about Mars.
      </div>

